<h1 class="blog--title">This Week in Spring - September 16th, 2014</h1>
<div class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon engineering"></div>
<a class="category">Engineering</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/fb22593caf24e4bb4c98d467cdd247e6?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<a class="author" rel="author" href="/team/jlong">Josh Long</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2014-09-16 19:29:00.0">September 16, 2014</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="1763" href="/blog/2014/09/16/this-week-in-spring-september-16th-2014#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</div>
</header>
<div class="blog--post"><p>Welcome to another installment of <em>This Week in Spring!</em> We&rsquo;re all back from last week&rsquo;s <em>epic</em> <a href="http://springone2gx.com">SpringOne2GX 2014</a>, but not resting on our laurels! As soon as I returned from SpringOne2GX, I set about preparing for this morning&rsquo;s webinar, <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2014/07/29/webinar-microservices-with-spring-boot-sept-16th"><em>Bootiful Microservices with Spring Boot</em></a>. That seems to have really resonated well and this is, principally, because <a href="https://spring.io/projects/spring-boot">Spring Boot</a> and <a href="https://spring.io/projects/spring-cloud">Spring Cloud</a> are <em>awesome</em>! I can&rsquo;t until all the amazing videos on the topic from SpringOne2GX and this webinar itself are available to share with you. To me it feels like a way for</p>
<ol>
<li>Spring for Android lead and mobile ninja Roy Clarkson announced <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2014/09/16/spring-for-android-2-0-0-m1-released">Spring for Android 2.0.0.M1 has been released</a>. The new release supports OkHttp (via the <code>OkHttpRequestFactory</code>), updates the included <code>RestTemplate</code> implementation to be on parity with the <code>RestTemplate</code> included with the Spring framework (including support for marshalling responses with a <code>ParameterizedTypeReference</code>). It raises the baseline to Android 2.2 (effectively), and includes numerous bug fixes and other improvements. This is the first new release in a long time - I&rsquo;d recommend getting and trying these bits ASAP!</li>
<li>I don&rsquo;t mean to tease, but you should at least read the good Dr. Syer and Spencer Gibb&rsquo;s slides to their <a href="https://speakerdeck.com/dsyer/spring-cloud-spring-boot-and-netflix-oss"> Spring Cloud talk at SpringOne2GX</a>. Great stuff.</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>Spring Security lead Rob Winch has written up a nice post <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2014/09/16/preview-spring-security-websocket-support-sessions">on using Spring Security with the Spring Session project and websockets</a>. Basically, if you&rsquo;re using JSR 356 (the websocket JSR), it&rsquo;s possible to need access to the HTTP session only to have it expire because the web-socket API doesn&rsquo;t keep it alive or make access easy. It&rsquo;s now possible to fix all that!</li>
<li>Speaking of Rob, a recording of a talk he gave - <a href="http://www.infoq.com/presentations/spring-boot-hello-world"><em>Spring Boot &hellip; Tweeting Complete Spring Applications Since 2013</em></a> - is now available on InfoQ! Check it out!</li>
<li>Did you miss last week&rsquo;s <em>epic</em> <strong>SpringOne2GX 2014</strong>? Have no fear! As usual, the videos will be available on <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2014/09/15/springone2gx-2014-day-2">Spring.io</a> in a trickle over the next few months, <em>and</em>, in the meantime, you can read the <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2014/09/10/springone2gx-2014-day-1">day 1</a> and <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2014/09/15/springone2gx-2014-day-2">day 2</a> recap posts.</li>
<li>ADTMag has a quick (albeit non-technical) news item <a href="https://adtmag.com/articles/2014/09/09/spring-framework-upgraded.aspx">on the recently released Spring framework 4.1</a></li>
<li>I just happened upon this <a href="http://www.infoq.com/interviews/Juergen-Hoeller-QConNY-2014-Interview">amazing interview of Spring framework lead Juergen Hoeller from QCon 2014 this year</a> on all manner of topics. Really good interview!</li>
<li>Nguyen Anh Tuan has an interesting post on <a href="https://sgdev-blog.blogspot.sg/2014/09/stateless-session-for-multi-tenant.html">how his group went about building a stateless and session-free, multi-tenant Spring Security implementation</a></li>
<li>A promisingly named blog, <em>TheSpringWay</em>, has a nice post on the <a href="http://thespringway.info/spring-web/dynamically-change-response-status-code/">convenient Spring MVC 4.1 improvements to response-code handling</a>. Did you know the historically slightly kludgy <code>ResponseEntity</code> has a nice builder API now?</li>
<li>the <em>JavaCodeGeeks</em> blog has a nice post on using <a href="http://www.javacodegeeks.com/2014/09/spring-batch-tutorial-with-spring-boot-and-java-configuration.html">Spring Batch with Spring Boot</a>. It&rsquo;s an interesting post for lots of reasons, not the least of which is that it also captures a user&rsquo;s first steps in Java configuration (which runs rampant in Spring Boot).</li>
<li>I had a lot of fun giving this morning&rsquo;s webinar. Join me next week for a webinar with my pal <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2014/07/29/webinar-process-driven-spring-applications-with-activiti-sept-23rd">Joram Barrez on building process-centric Spring Boot and Activiti BPMN2 workflow engine</a>!</li>
</ul></div>
</div>
